---
import Article from '../../layouts/Article.astro';
import ExpandableSection from '../../components/ExpandableSection.svelte';
---

<Article
  title="Financial Stress"
  subtitle="Recognizing it, naming it, working through it."
  branch="self"
  backHref="/self"
  backLabel="Self"
  readTime="5 min"
>

  <p>
    Financial stress isn't a personal failing. It's what happens when the gap between
    what you need and what you have feels impossible to close. It affects your sleep,
    your relationships, your health, your ability to think clearly about anything else.
  </p>

  <p>
    And it's common. A majority of Canadians report financial stress, and for people
    in communities that have been systematically underfunded for generations, the
    stress is compounded by factors you didn't create.
  </p>

  <h2>What financial stress looks like</h2>

  <p>It's not always obvious. Some signs:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Avoiding opening mail, checking your bank account, or answering the phone</li>
    <li>Lying awake at night thinking about bills or money</li>
    <li>Arguing with family about spending</li>
    <li>Feeling ashamed about your financial situation</li>
    <li>Spending impulsively when stressed (it temporarily relieves anxiety)</li>
    <li>Physical symptoms — headaches, stomach problems, tension</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you recognize yourself in that list, you're not alone and you're not broken.
    This is a normal human response to financial pressure.
  </p>

  <h2>The historical layer</h2>

  <p>
    It's worth naming this: for many Indigenous people, financial stress carries an
    extra weight. Generations of disrupted economies — the pass system, the potlatch
    ban, residential schools severing the transfer of economic knowledge — created
    financial trauma that shows up in families today.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's not an excuse. It's context. Understanding where the stress comes from
    is part of working through it.
  </p>

  <h2>Practical steps</h2>

  <ExpandableSection client:idle title="The 'look at it' step">
    <p class="text-sm">
      The single most powerful thing you can do is look at your situation clearly.
      Not to judge it — just to see it. Open your bank app. Look at what came in
      last month. Look at what went out. That's it. You don't have to fix anything
      yet. Just looking reduces the anxiety that comes from avoidance.
    </p>
  </ExpandableSection>

  <ExpandableSection client:idle title="Name the biggest worry">
    <p class="text-sm">
      What's the one thing keeping you up? A specific bill? Rent? Debt collectors?
      A vague sense of "not enough"? Naming it makes it smaller. Vague financial
      dread is harder to deal with than a specific problem. Specific problems have
      specific solutions.
    </p>
  </ExpandableSection>

  <ExpandableSection client:idle title="Take one action">
    <p class="text-sm">
      Not ten. One. Call the utility company and ask about a payment plan. Set up
      direct deposit so you don't lose money to cheque-cashing fees. Check if you're
      getting the GST credit. File last year's taxes. One thing. The momentum from
      one action makes the next one easier.
    </p>
  </ExpandableSection>

  <ExpandableSection client:idle title="Talk to someone">
    <p class="text-sm">
      Financial shame thrives in silence. Talking to a trusted person — a family
      member, an elder, a friend, a counsellor — breaks the shame cycle. If you
      need professional support, NIHB covers mental health counselling. Your band's
      health centre can connect you. The crisis line is also available 24/7: Hope
      for Wellness Helpline at 1-855-242-3310 (counselling available in Cree,
      Ojibway, and Inuktitut).
    </p>
  </ExpandableSection>

  <h2>What not to do</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Don't ignore it.</strong> Financial problems almost never improve on their own. They compound.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't borrow from payday lenders.</strong> They exist to profit from your stress. The interest rates are predatory.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't compare.</strong> Social media shows everyone's best day. Your financial situation is your own — comparing it to someone else's curated life helps nobody.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't isolate.</strong> The impulse to withdraw when you're stressed about money is strong. Resist it. Community is your strongest asset.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout callout-tip">
    <strong>Financial stress is temporary</strong>
    <p>
      Your financial situation is a snapshot, not a sentence. It can change. People
      who take even small steps consistently find that the stress lifts — not because
      all the problems disappear, but because they stop feeling helpless about them.
    </p>
  </div>

</Article>
